Implementing a custom std::unique_ptr is a classic system-level C++ exercise. It demonstrates a deep understanding of RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization), move semantics, and Rule of Five memory management.

Here is a production-ready, interview-grade implementation of a custom unique_ptr.

The Core Principles
To make this work, the class must enforce exclusive ownership:

No Copying: We must explicitly delete the copy constructor and copy assignment operator.

Move Semantics: We must implement the move constructor and move assignment operator to transfer the internal pointer and nullify the source.

RAII: The destructor must automatically clean up the memory.

C++ Implementation
C++
#include <iostream>
#include <utility> // for std::exchange

template <typename T>
class UniquePtr {
private:
    T* ptr_;

public:
    // 1. Default Constructor
    constexpr UniquePtr() noexcept : ptr_(nullptr) {}

    // 2. Explicit Constructor (prevents implicit conversions like UniquePtr<int> p = new int)
    explicit UniquePtr(T* p) noexcept : ptr_(p) {}

    // 3. Destructor (RAII)
    ~UniquePtr() {
        delete ptr_;
    }

    // 4. Delete Copy Constructor and Copy Assignment
    // This enforces exclusive ownership. You cannot copy a unique_ptr.
    UniquePtr(const UniquePtr&) = delete;
    UniquePtr& operator=(const UniquePtr&) = delete;

    // 5. Move Constructor
    // Transfer ownership from 'other' to 'this', then nullify 'other'
    UniquePtr(UniquePtr&& other) noexcept : ptr_(other.ptr_) {
        other.ptr_ = nullptr;
    }

    // 6. Move Assignment Operator
    UniquePtr& operator=(UniquePtr&& other) noexcept {
        // Prevent self-assignment (e.g., p = std::move(p))
        if (this != &other) {
            delete ptr_;             // Clean up our current resource
            ptr_ = other.ptr_;       // Take ownership
            other.ptr_ = nullptr;    // Nullify the source
        }
        return *this;
    }

    // --- Observers ---

    // Return the raw pointer
    T* get() const noexcept {
        return ptr_;
    }

    // Dereference operator
    T& operator*() const {
        return *ptr_;
    }

    // Member access operator
    T* operator->() const noexcept {
        return ptr_;
    }

    // Boolean conversion to check if it holds a valid pointer (e.g., if (ptr) { ... })
    explicit operator bool() const noexcept {
        return ptr_ != nullptr;
    }

    // --- Modifiers ---

    // Relinquish ownership and return the raw pointer. 
    // The caller is now responsible for deleting it.
    T* release() noexcept {
        T* temp = ptr_;
        ptr_ = nullptr;
        return temp;
        // In C++14/17, you can write this as a one-liner:
        // return std::exchange(ptr_, nullptr);
    }

    // Destroy the current object and take ownership of a new one.
    void reset(T* p = nullptr) noexcept {
        T* old_ptr = ptr_;
        ptr_ = p;        // Update internal pointer FIRST
        delete old_ptr;  // Delete old pointer LAST to be exception-safe
    }
};
Usage Example
Here is how you would use it in practice, proving that the RAII and Move mechanics work as expected:

C++
class Resource {
public:
    Resource() { std::cout << "Resource Acquired\n"; }
    ~Resource() { std::cout << "Resource Destroyed\n"; }
    void doSomething() { std::cout << "Doing something...\n"; }
};

int main() {
    std::cout << "--- 1. Creating ptr1 ---\n";
    UniquePtr<Resource> ptr1(new Resource());
    
    if (ptr1) {
        ptr1->doSomething();
    }

    std::cout << "\n--- 2. Moving ptr1 to ptr2 ---\n";
    // UniquePtr<Resource> ptr2 = ptr1; // ERROR: Call to deleted copy constructor
    UniquePtr<Resource> ptr2 = std::move(ptr1); // SUCCESS: Ownership transferred
    
    if (!ptr1) {
        std::cout << "ptr1 is now null.\n";
    }
    ptr2->doSomething();

    std::cout << "\n--- 3. End of scope ---\n";
    // ptr2 goes out of scope and automatically deletes the Resource.
    return 0;
}
What makes this "Production Grade"?
While this captures the core mechanics of std::unique_ptr, a senior C++ engineer should be aware of what is missing in this simplified version compared to the standard library:

Custom Deleters: The real std::unique_ptr has a second template parameter: template <typename T, typename Deleter = std::default_delete<T>>. This allows you to provide custom cleanup functions (e.g., fclose for a file pointer, or a custom memory pool release).

Empty Base Class Optimization (EBCO): To support Custom Deleters without increasing the size of the unique_ptr object (a raw pointer is 8 bytes; unique_ptr should also be exactly 8 bytes), the standard library uses EBCO or [[no_unique_address]] in C++20.

Array Specialization: The standard provides a template specialization for arrays (std::unique_ptr<T[]>), which correctly calls delete[] instead of delete and provides operator[].

std::make_unique: You would typically implement a variadic template function MakeUnique<T>(Args&&... args) to safely construct the object and wrap it in the pointer, preventing memory leaks if an exception is thrown during argument evaluation.

